[2]
From: jaltamira@hline.localhealth.net
Date: 30 Jul 1997 15:50:56 EST

I am an epidemiologist who was born in Cuenca, Ecuador. Through this
exceptional line of communication I am always keeping track of what is
going on in Latin America, especially in Ecuador. As epidemiologist I
immediately start wondering if this outbreak is explained by special
weather conditions or other factors affecting mosquito population? Or if
similar conditions are maintained, is the Ecuadorian army continuously
exposed to similar risk? What is the baseline observation of cases in this
geographic area? Besides in the last couple of weeks we received the
notification that unidentified disease was responsible for several deaths
in the same Amazonic area and other surrounding provinces. I am not
suggesting a direct connection of these two outbreaks but it will be
important to rule out any common factor.
I deeply appreciate Ecuadorian researchers keeping us informed of this kind
of occurrences.
--
Dr. Jaime V. Altamirano,
Epidemiologist
Michigan Department of Health
phone 517 3558175, fax 517 335 8121
altamiranoj@state.mi.us
